Blog Post - Contributors to Teen Birth Rate

Dara Zirlin, Ran Ji

Last updated on 2019-05-29

Given the recent policy changes around abortion, we wanted to study some of the possible contributors to teenage birth rates around the US. Towards this, we found county-level data for unemployment, adult education level, and median household income. Our hypothesis was that teenage birth rates is positively correlated with unemployment rate and negatively correlated with education level and median household income. We were also interested whether there were signifant regional differences in teenage birth rates in the US, keeping the other variables constant.

Before we share our findings, we briefly describe the datasets. The teen birth rate is the number of females age 15-19 that have given birth per 1000 females age 15-19. We used data from 2015. As a reminder, unemployment rate is the percentage of the labor force (people with a job or actively looking for one) without a job. Here we also use data from 2015. Our educational data categorizes adults into four groups: did not receive high school diploma, only received high school diploma, some college or associate’s degree, and received college degree or higher. The datasets we found did contains the average percent of adults in each category for 2013-2017.

Graphics

Below, we plot our independent variables against teen birth rates.

There appears to be a clear positive relationship between teen birth rates and the percent of adults with less than a high school diploma.
